{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}} {{Use British English|date=January 2017}}
The '''BROACH warhead''' is a [[Tandem-charge|multi-stage warhead]] developed by Team BROACH; [[BAE Systems Global Combat Systems Munitions]], [[Thales Missile Electronics]] and [[QinetiQ]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themanufacturer.com/uk/profile/6848/BAE_Systems_Land_Systems_Munitions?PHPSESSID=c88 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-02-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610230958/http://www.themanufacturer.com/uk/profile/6848/BAE_Systems_Land_Systems_Munitions?PHPSESSID=c88 |archivedate=10 June 2011 }}</ref> BROACH stands for '''''B'''omb '''R'''oyal '''O'''rdnance '''A'''ugmented '''CH'''arge''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Munitions products|url=http://www.baesystems.com/en/product/munition-products|publisher=[[BAE Systems]]|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref>
Development of BROACH began in 1991 when Team BROACH consisted of [[British Aerospace]] [[Royal Ordnance|RO Defence]], [[Thomson-CSF|Thomson-Thorn Missile Electronics]] and [[Defence Evaluation and Research Agency|DERA]]. The two stage warhead is made up from an initial [[shaped charge]], which cuts a passage through armour, concrete, earth, etc., allowing a larger following warhead to penetrate inside the target. The weapon is designed to allow a cruise missile to achieve the degree of hard-target penetration formerly only possible by the use of [[Laser-guided bomb|laser-guided]] gravity bombs.
==Applications== * [[Storm Shadow]]/SCALP EG * [[AGM-154 Joint Standoff Weapon]] unitary variant (JSOW-C)<ref>[http://www.na.baesystems.com/releasesDetail.cfm?a=127 "BAE Systems JSOW Unitary BROACH program enters operational test" - BAE Systems plc (Jan. 5, 2004) Press release.]</ref> * BROACH was evaluated as a possible warhead for the [[AGM-86D CALCM]] but was ultimately not selected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boeing.com/news/releases/1999/news_release_991202o.htm |title=Boeing Selects Lockheed Martin to Provide CALCM Hard-Target Warhead |accessdate=15 April 2018 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001209180000/http://www.boeing.com:80/news/releases/1999/news_release_991202o.htm |archivedate=9 December 2001}}</ref> * [[SOM (missile)]] B2 variant.
