The '''Field Ration Eating Device''' (F.R.E.D. or FRED) is a small device which is a combination of a can opener, a bottle opener and a spoon. It is issued to the [[Australian Defence Force]] in its [[Combat Ration One Man|CR1M]] ration packs.<ref>{{cite web | date = 2005-10-06 | url = http://www.defence.gov.au/news/armynews/editions/1130/letters.htm  | title = Farewell, old Fred | work = Army - The Soldiers' Newspaper 6 October 2005 Edition #1130 : Letters to the Editor  | publisher = Coordination and Public Affairs; Directorate of Defence Newspapers (Australian Army) | accessdate = 2007-11-05 }}  and {{cite web  | date = 2005-10-20 | url =http://www.defence.gov.au/news/armynews/editions/1131/letters.htm | title = Fred’s friend’s left with sour taste | work = Army - The Soldiers' Newspaper 20 October 2005 Edition #1131 : Letters to the Editor | publisher = Australian Army | accessdate =2007-11-05 }}</ref> It is also known widely as the "Fucking Ridiculous Eating Device".<ref>{{cite web  | last =   | first =   | authorlink =   | coauthors =   | year = 2005 | url = http://www.metafilter.com/45321/A-history-of-modern-military-rations| title = A history of modern military rations  | work =  | publisher = MetaFilter:community weblog | accessdate = 2007-11-05 |quote = A similar device is currently employed by the Australian Army in its ration kits. It is known by the acronym "FRED" (Fucking Ridiculous Eating Device).}}</ref><ref>{{cite web  | last = Hardiman  | first = Graeme  | url = http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-conflicts-periods/malaya-korea/malaya-2rar.htm| title = The Malayan Emergency. 2RAR 1956/57 | work = 2RAR | publisher = Digger History:  an unofficial history of the Australian & New Zealand Armed Forces  | accessdate = 2007-11-05 |quote = I remember the spoon come tin opener that was in later years nicknamed "Fred" (F****ing ridiculous eating device)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|year=2007 |url=http://www.militarypeople.com.au/mainsite/content/view/175/50/ |title=Australian Ration pack Contents |work=Ration Pack |publisher=Australian Defence News & Opinion - MilitaryPeople.com.au |accessdate=2007-11-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012083346/http://www.militarypeople.com.au/mainsite/content/view/175/50/ |archivedate=2007-10-12 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>

The can opener is very similar in design to the US military [[P-38 can opener]].

